<paper id="1600432225"><title>One Way Hash Functions and DES</title><year>1989</year><authors><author org="Xerox-PARC" id="2805948211">Ralph C. Merkle</author></authors><n_citation>711</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1543503103</reference><reference>1566345534</reference><reference>1600255172</reference><reference>1813564308</reference><reference>1972792640</reference><reference>1991374982</reference><reference>2109394932</reference><reference>2155099317</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/0-387-34805-0_40</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.69196">SHA-2</keyword><keyword weight="0.43566">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.71754">Cryptographic hash function</keyword><keyword weight="0.43658">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.70305">Hash function</keyword><keyword weight="0.69824">Secure Hash Standard</keyword><keyword weight="0.67918">Security of cryptographic hash functions</keyword><keyword weight="0.68644">Hash chain</keyword><keyword weight="0.69587">Secure Hash Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.77361">MDC-2</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer-Verlag New York, Inc.</publisher><abstract>One way hash functions are a major tool in cryptography. DES is the best known and most widely used encryption function in the commercial world today. Generating a one-way hash function which is secure if DES is a "good" block cipher would therefore be useful. We show three such functions which are secure if DES is a good random block cipher.</abstract></paper>